    "Under the baseline Hotelling model (Hotelling (1929); Downs (1957)), we obtain the standard Downsian convergence result, where both political parties choose to cater to the median voter's preferences by setting x * L = x * R = 1/2 in the unique equilibrium.",
    "One of our key results will be that because of the effects of AI-powered online business strategies, we will generally have policy differentiation-",
    "This arises because voters near the poles are less likely to vote for a candidate that has a platform misaligned with their ideology, driving the parties' incentives to differentiate themselves (as opposed to the standard framework, where such forces are muted).",
